    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1982-03-09T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1982-03-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="85"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d85">
                <head>85. Memorandum From <persName corresp="#p_BNA_1">Norman Bailey</persName> of
                    the National Security Council Staff to the President’s Assistant for National
                    Security Affairs (Clark)<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d85fn1">Source: Reagan
                        Library, Executive Secretariat, <gloss target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss> Agency
                        File, Department of State (02/13/1982–05/25/1982). Secret. Sent for action.
                        A stamped notation reads: “SIGNED.” <persName corresp="#p_WMO_1"
                            >Wheeler</persName> initialed the top right-hand corner of the
                        memorandum.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1982-03-09">March 9, 1982</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Secretary <persName corresp="#p_HAM_1">Haig</persName>’s Recommendation
                        Concerning the Establishment of an Institute for <rs
                            corresp="recOWsM3ry8STSsK3" type="topic">Democracy</rs>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>Secretary <persName corresp="#p_HAM_1">Haig</persName> has written a memo to the
                    President (Tab A) in which he urges that the President “. . . endorse the
                    establishment of an Institute for <rs corresp="recOWsM3ry8STSsK3" type="topic"
                        >Democracy</rs>.”<note n="2" xml:id="d85fn2">See <ref target="#d84">Document
                            84</ref>.</note> The purpose of this Institute, which would be private,
                    would be to train and help <rs corresp="recy5FvpH0k4sOWVY" type="topic"
                        >finance</rs> democratic leaders from the Soviet Bloc and the <gloss
                        target="#t_LDC_1">LDC</gloss>’s.</p>
                <p>His suggestion has serious problems, such as: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>How would the Institute get hold of “democratic leaders” from the
                            Soviet Bloc for <rs corresp="recWvvPjLhJgF9yYo" type="topic"
                                >training</rs>, and how would they be reintroduced into their
                            countries?</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>The Institute, if sponsored by the government, or “endorsed” by it,
                            would be seen by all as a government initiative.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>Friendly authoritarian governments among the <gloss target="#t_LDC_1"
                                >LDC</gloss>’s would see it as an attempt to destabilize
                            them.</item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>Finally, and most important, dictatorship, whether authoritarian or
                            totalitarian, can be imposed, <rs corresp="recOWsM3ry8STSsK3"
                                type="topic">democracy</rs> can’t. The Soviets can be sure that if a
                            Communist <rs corresp="recgHSq0J1Seyqrw9" type="topic">coup</rs> is
                            successful, a Communist government will result. No one can know what
                            will result from a “democratic” <rs corresp="recgHSq0J1Seyqrw9"
                                type="topic">coup</rs>, as several centuries of history
                            testify.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>Incidentally, under Clif White’s leadership, the Republican Party is beginning to
                    get more involved in international cooperation. This process should be
                    encouraged.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_LCR_1">Carnes Lord</persName> and <persName
                        corresp="#p_SWL_1">William Stearman</persName> concur with my recommendation
                    that the President disapprove the suggestion in Secretary <persName
                        corresp="#p_HAM_1">Haig</persName>’s memo.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_MAA_1">Al Myer</persName>, Dick Childress, <persName
                        corresp="#p_SCC_1">Chris Shoemaker</persName>, Dick Pipes and <persName
                        corresp="#p_RJM_1">Jim Rentschler</persName> believe that further <rs
                        corresp="rectXll6XKk0xZnDr" type="topic">exploration</rs> of the concept is
                    necessary on an <rs corresp="recWMZ9EcUPmDYpbT" type="topic">interagency</rs>
                    basis to address the numerous aspects of this idea prior to the establishment of
                    a specific program. <persName corresp="#p_MAA_1">Myer</persName>, Childress <pb
                        facs="0385" n="316" xml:id="pg_316"/> and <persName corresp="#p_SCC_1"
                        >Shoemaker</persName> have provided an alternative memo to Secretary
                        <persName corresp="#p_HAM_1">Haig</persName> (Tab II) suggesting that the
                    proposal be examined in greater detail.<note n="3" xml:id="d85fn3">Not
                        attached.</note>
                </p>
                <p rend="sectiontitleital">Recommendation:</p>
                <p>That you sign the memorandum to the President at Tab I recommending that he
                    disapprove the suggestion in Secretary <persName corresp="#p_HAM_1"
                        >Haig</persName>’s memo.<note n="4" xml:id="d85fn4">Clark placed a checkmark
                        on the “Approve” line. Tab I, Clark’s memorandum to the President, is
                        Document 87.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Alternatively, that you sign the memorandum to Secretary <persName
                        corresp="#p_HAM_1">Haig</persName> at Tab II suggesting that the proposal be
                    examined in greater detail before the establishment of a specific
                    organization.</p>
            </div>
